In your original code:

```html
&lt;template v-for=&quot;item in schedules&quot;&gt;
  &lt;td v-if=&quot;days.includes(item.day)&quot; class=&quot;text-left&quot;&gt;{{item.from_time}}-{{item.to_time}}&lt;/td&gt;
  &lt;td v-else class=&quot;text-left&quot;&gt;-&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/template&gt;
```

There are a couple issues:

 1. You&#39;re iterating only `schedules`, which could be fewer than the number of days in a week (as is the case in your example).
 2. The `v-if` checks if `days` includes the item&#39;s day number, which will likely be true (assuming your data always fits the domain), so this effectively makes the table render all the `schedules` items in order.


One solution is to use `Array.prototype.map` on `days` (i.e., the array of day IDs that `schedules[].day` maps to) in a computed prop:

```js
export default {
  computed: {
    weekly() {
      return this.days.map(day =&gt; this.schedules.find(s =&gt; s.day == day))
    }
  }
}
```

...and update your template to use that prop:


```html
&lt;template v-for=&quot;item in weekly&quot;&gt;
  &lt;td v-if=&quot;item&quot; class=&quot;text-left&quot;&gt;{{item.from_time}}-{{item.to_time}}&lt;/td&gt;
  &lt;td v-else class=&quot;text-left&quot;&gt;-&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/template&gt;
```

